  <div class="topic">
    <h4>Snippets</h4>
    <p>Another great setting in Sublime is "Snippets". Is there some code that you're writing over and over again and wish to recall at any time? Such as your boilderplate HTML? Make a snippet! For that, go to <c>Tools - New Snippet</c>. This is what you will see by default:</p>

    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8"><span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;<span style="color:#89bdff">snippet</span>></span>
  <span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;<span style="color:#89bdff">content</span>></span><span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;!<span style="color:#3387cc">[CDATA[
Hello, ${1:this} is a ${2:snippet}.
]]</span>></span><span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;/<span style="color:#89bdff">content</span>></span>
  <span style="color:#aeaeae;font-style:italic">&lt;!-- Optional: Set a tabTrigger to define how to trigger the snippet --></span>
  <span style="color:#aeaeae;font-style:italic">&lt;!-- &lt;tabTrigger>hello&lt;/tabTrigger> --></span>
  <span style="color:#aeaeae;font-style:italic">&lt;!-- Optional: Set a scope to limit where the snippet will trigger --></span>
  <span style="color:#aeaeae;font-style:italic">&lt;!-- &lt;scope>source.python&lt;/scope> --></span>
<span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;/<span style="color:#89bdff">snippet</span>></span>
</pre>

    <p>In place of <c>Hello, ${1:this} is a ${2:snippet}.</c> you will place the code you want to save and recall later. To create the "trigger word", uncomment the <c>tabTrigger</c> line and put what you want, like this:</p>

    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8"><span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;<span style="color:#89bdff">snippet</span>></span>
  <span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;<span style="color:#89bdff">content</span>></span><span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;!<span style="color:#3387cc">[CDATA[
Hello, ${1:this} is a ${2:snippet}.
]]</span>></span><span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;/<span style="color:#89bdff">content</span>></span>
  <span style="color:#aeaeae;font-style:italic">&lt;!-- Optional: Set a tabTrigger to define how to trigger the snippet --></span>
  <span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;<span style="color:#89bdff">tabTrigger</span>></span>hello<span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;/<span style="color:#89bdff">tabTrigger</span>></span>
  <span style="color:#aeaeae;font-style:italic">&lt;!-- Optional: Set a scope to limit where the snippet will trigger --></span>
  <span style="color:#aeaeae;font-style:italic">&lt;!-- &lt;scope>source.python&lt;/scope> --></span>
<span style="color:#89bdff">&lt;/<span style="color:#89bdff">snippet</span>></span>
</pre>

    <p>Now if you save this file (it must have a <c>.sublime-snippet</c> extension) and go to any file in sublime you can recall this text. To recall this snippet you would type <c>hello</c> and press 'tab'. It should print <c>Hello, this is a snippet.</c>. If you press tab again, your cursor will stop on 'this', and if you press tab a second time your cursor will stop on 'snippet'. This is becasue we added this to it: <c>${1:this}</c> and <c>${2:snippet}</c>.</p>

    <p>Now, practice this by adding your own snippet.</p>
